</paragraph>
<paragraph pageNumber="454">Types Mus. Comp. Zool. Harvard.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="etymology">
<paragraph pageNumber="454">
etymology 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181901" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole micon Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole micon Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="micon">Micon</taxonomicName>
, a painter and sculptor of ancient Athens.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageNumber="454">
diagnosis A medium-sized member of the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33744" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole flavens Roger" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole flavens Roger" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavens">flavens</taxonomicName>
group; most immediately recognizable by the striking bicolorous condition of both castes (see below). Most similar in the remainder of its anatomy to 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33632" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole breviseta Santschi" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole breviseta Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="breviseta">breviseta</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181849" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole bruchella Forel" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole bruchella Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bruchella">bruchella</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181886" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pheidole hizemops Wilson" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole hizemops Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="454" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hizemops">hizemops</taxonomicName>
, differing in details of sculpturing and form of the mesosoma, petiole, and postpetiole, as illustrated. measurements (mm) Holotype major: HW 0.94, HL 0.96, SL 0.50, EL 0.14, PW 0.42. Paratype minor: HW 0.44, HL 0.52, SL 0.42, EL 0.06, PW 0.28. color Major: bicolorous, body dark brown, appendages dark yellow.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="description">
<paragraph pageNumber="454">Minor: bicolorous, postpetiole and gaster medium to brownish yellow, rest of body medium brown, appendages medium yellow.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="454">range Known only from the type series.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph pageNumber="454">biology Found in a rotting log in a coffee plantation (cafetal).</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection type="materials_examined">
<paragraph pageNumber="454">Figure Upper: holotype, major. Lower: paratype, minor. COLOMBIA: San Pedro de la Sierra, Magdalena, Colombia, 1300 m (Charles Kugler). Scale bars = 1 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
